<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by Cranfield University’s Centre for Environmental Risks and Futures (CERF) (GSH0005)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:center; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Cranfield</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> University’s Centre for Environmental Risks and Futures (CERF) (GSH0005)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">Introduction</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Cranfield University’s Centre for Environmental Risks and Futures </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">(CERF) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">welcomes this opportunity to offer written evidence to the Science and Technology Committee’s inquiry into </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Government Horizon Scanning. CERF </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">forms part of the Department for Environmental Science and Technology in Cranfield University’s School of Applied S</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">cience</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">CERF </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">is currently commissioned by Defra to provide a full programme of horizon scanning and futures research to the Department, its network of agencies and both the Scottish and Welsh Governments. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">On behalf of Cranfield University, this </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">evidence</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">has been prepared by Fiona Lickorish, who is Head of the Centre for Environmental Risks and Futures at Cranfield University. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Fiona Lickorish</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> has over 20 years experience in undertaking environmental futures research and long-term impact assessment in the private, third and public sectors. She joined Cranfield University in April 2011, prior to which she was Head of Horizon Scanning and Futures</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> at Defra from 2005 to 2011, where she led a programme of futures research, that included a review of all the research undertaken within the Defra Futures Programme between 2002 and 2005. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Horizon scanning is one of a number of tools that futures research</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ers use which can be employed to test future policy and strategy</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. P</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ractitioners do not normally use the term horizon scanning to describe all futures research techniques: it is one method in a wider toolkit used by futures research practitioners</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> act of gathering new insights that may point us towards affirming or discrediting existing trends and developments, as well as identifying new and emerging trends and developments which will impact on our lives in the future.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> The Jon Day Review appears to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> use the term to describe wider futures research methods. For the purposes of this submission, we will use the term ‘futures research’ to describe the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> full range of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> methods used by futures practitioners to analyse possible futures. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Where the term ‘horizon </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">scanning</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> is used, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">it describes the action set out above. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">1.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">There are a number of observable differences in undertaking futures research from other, perhaps more familiar research methods. We do not go into detail here, but suggest that should Committee me</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">mbers so wish, they may find value in reading the review of futures research undertaken by Defra (2006), but which does not appear as part of the literature review undertaken as part of the Day Review. We consider that a good understanding of these differe</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">nces is key in helping Ministers and senior officials to understand, develop and use the outputs of futures research. Additionally, it should be noted that a number of the recommendations made in the Day Review reflect those identified in the earlier Defra</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> work. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">Key Points</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Used well, futures research can gain efficiencies in policy-making</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> leading to good value for the taxpayer. </span></li></ul></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Prior to commissioning, potential users of futures research need to recogni</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">e and make available, the correct amount of resour</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ces </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">necessary </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">for success</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">: this is as much about the commitment of sufficient time and engagement, as it is financial investment</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ul></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Ministers and senior officials, together with those who intend to commission, manage and/or use the outputs of futures research </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">should familiarise themselves with both the applicability and the limitations of this type of research: we suggest that this req</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">uires relevant </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">capacity building</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> involving </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">at least 1 day’s training. </span></li></ul></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Practitioners working with Government should contemplate the use of more familiar risk management language </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and embedding </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">risk analysis methods in the futures research process</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to he</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">lp users understand how outputs can </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">better inform </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the policy-making process.  </span></li></ul></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Departments should consider where best to position the commissioning and management of futures research</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> projects</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> to complement the social science methods employed.  </span></li></ul></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The appoi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ntment of high-level champions to embed futures thinking across Government and within </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">D</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">epartments is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">key</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ul></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Government </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">understanding and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">use of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">basic</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">futures research terminology, as recognised by practitioners, would help to remove the potential for costl</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">y misunderstandings between Government and practitioners. </span></li></ul></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">How do Government departments make use of horizon scanning?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">3.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Government departments, and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">often </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">groups within departments, vary both in the way they use futures research, and in the depth to which they </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">apply such </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">research</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> to policy and practice</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. In our experience the main uses are to: </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Inform policy</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">making / decision</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">making processes</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and reviews.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Help to organise where funds are best spent, e.g. to inform evidence investment strategies. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Identify issues not on the current political / policy making agenda, but which might need to be dealt with in future, i.e. emergent issues and opportunities. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">To e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ngage with stakeholders to develop future partnerships for action</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> around emergent </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">issues for public policy</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">More recently we have been working with Government to use futures research to help to inform risk analysis processes</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, for example, to inform risk </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">mitigation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">refore, to identify</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> possible factors that might impact on current or planned policy</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">How effective is horizon scanning in Government? Do Ministers and senior officials consider horizon scanning outputs appropriately?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The effectiveness o</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">f futures research in Government is variable, and is conditioned by a range of factors, some of which are internal to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">D</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">epartments, some of which are driven by external imperatives and pressures.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Below, we identify some key factors that</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, in our experience,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> condition whether futures research is effective or not.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">One key factor is the need for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">considerable resource input from, and engagement by, domain experts</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">(e.g. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">scientific specialists in the subject in question</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, and policy- and decision-makers in Govern</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ment. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Whilst successful research generally requires a measure of user engagement</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">effective </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">futures research requires continuous involvement of those wishing to use the outputs of the research from procurement to delivery. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">In short, t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">o benefit from </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">futures</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">research</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">requires</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">an investment of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">sustained effort from all those involved, things that are often in short supply in today’s Government. Lack of time </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">understandably </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">often leads officials</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Ministers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to have to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">concentrate on delivery of the current age</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">nda with little time to focus on the future. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The effectiveness of futures research is dependent on those commissioning the research understand</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> what it can, but </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">equally</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> importantly, what it cannot provide. For example, there is a tendency to want prediction</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. Futures</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> research cannot provide </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">this because the future is generally not predictable</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> so </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the research is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> a tool </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> enable policy</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">makers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and politicians </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to reflect on</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> how their recommendations and decisions might unfold in a number of possible futures rather than rely on a single explicit or implicit route to the future. This is important, for example, in infrastructure planning and implementation given the timescales </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">involved which can span decades</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">: the imperatives of today, may - or may not - be relevant at the point at which the infrastructure development is completed, so thinking in structured terms about what that future might look like should be helpful</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Therefor</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">e, to be truly effective, futures research should be used as a tool to enable policy</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">makers to test assumptions against a range of possible futures, and to provide orientation around how policy development and decision</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">making may work – or may need to work</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> – in the future. The outputs will not be a reflection of the status quo: some methods are specifically designed to shift recipients from their current world view and to enable them to think about what is possible and plausible, not just what is probable. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">It can therefore create discomfort because it challenges the current world view.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Using f</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">utures research can be</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> challenged by the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">pragmatic </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">need to b</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">alanc</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> responding to immediate policy imperatives</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> against emergent ones or those where impacts may not be f</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">elt until years to come. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Harold M</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">cMillan may be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">mis</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">quoted in apparently speaking of  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">“events</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> dear boy</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> events”</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, but there is a reality in</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> this that often favours</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the immediate </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">rather than </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">emergen</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">t.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Yet, considering the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">future</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">can enable a more </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">efficient and effective use of diminishing resources</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> which has the potential to gain savings for the tax payer</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. P</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">olicies that are </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">future</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">proofed</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> can be more sustainable and adaptable to changing circumstances, which saves resources. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">For </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">example</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">futures</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> research </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">(in this case, grounded in understanding demography) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">could have </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">helped school place planning:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> we effectively count births and changes in the birth rate, yet seem challenged to relate this to planning the requisite number of school places.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">4.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Politi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">cians as well as policy makers can find futures research challenging: a proportion understand and engage with it and promote its use, bu</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">t </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the imperatives of short-term pressures </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">may </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">simply crowd out </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">taking the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">longer-term view</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> that often drives the reason </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to engage in politics in the first </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">place. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We understand th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, not least in an era of economic challenge and austerity, but suggest that better embedding of futures research into the fabric </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">decision-making, coupled with senior political </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and official’s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">su</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">pport for it, might help in balancing the short- and longer-terms.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">What changes could be made to improve existing horizon scanning activity? Will the recommendations made in Jon Day’s review of cross-government horizon scanning capability address current shortcomings? What progress has been made implementing these? </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We be</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">lieve that the Day recommendations are generally well founded, but that some further nuances and steps would help to deliver the recommendations.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.2</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Futures research uses recognised social science and organisational management participatory </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">methods (expert e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">licitation interviews, questionnaires and workshop techniques)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, coupled with secondary research including desk-based analysis of relevant research and datasets,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> to identify all aspects of whichever issue being investigated. These include using domain exper</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ts to identify and understand the interactions between the political, economic, social, technological, legislative and environmental drivers of change (PESTLE analysis), to gain an understanding of whole systems, rather than projections of individual drive</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">rs</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> of change</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Given this, i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">may </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">be best placed under the management of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Government social science profession whose members have a better understanding of the utility of the outputs of research using social science techniques.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.3</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Currently</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, many futures </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">research projects</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and programmes</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> are managed by and report to, central departmental evidence and strategy teams. The research programmes of these teams </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">can be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">dominated by economic research and managed by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">specialists</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> whose training </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">rightly </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">lends them to gi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ve more weight to data</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> sourced by more traditional means</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, but who can sometimes find it </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">challenging</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> to understand and give credence to the less </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">defined</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> outputs gathered using </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">futures research methods</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. Futures research outputs therefore, are</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> often perceived</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> to be less robust</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, which can lead to a perception that there is less imperative to take action</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. Many </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">specialist</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> evidence managers and policy-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">makers are therefore, reluctant to allocate precious time and resources to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">issues identified by futures resear</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ch until a greater weight of evidence to sup</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">port action is available. T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">here is a delicate balance to be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">struck</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> between acting too early and potentially wasting resources or waiting until the weight of evidence is overwhelming</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. However, this has potential to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">leav</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> action too late</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">: at best, this may involve additional cost, at worst, it results in the sort of failure that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">policy process seeks to avoid.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.4</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Futures research has a creative dimension and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">methods are often describ</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ed in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">language that isn’t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> necessarily familiar to policy-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">makers. We </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">find</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">describing outputs </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">using the language of risk </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">assessment and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">man</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">agement</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">which is more familiar to Government senior officials, can greatly assist in embedding understanding</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. Cra</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">nfield University has pioneered the integration of risk analysis tools to complement the outputs of futures research with more robust analysis of where future risks and opportunities might lie, and where and when to intervene to gain best value for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">the tax</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">payer. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">However, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">whilst this has helped improve use of outputs for those already familiar with risk terminology, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">we also identify that training for officials needs to include developing familiarity and understanding of the applications and benefits of both </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">futures and risk research in the policy-making community. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Additionally</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, the involvement of Departmental risk managers can be key in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">challenging, supporting and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">embedding the outputs of futures research with </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">policy-makers, senior officials and politicians. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.5</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Whilst the Day Review sets out a new definition for ‘horizon scanning’ </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">across Government </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">this actually appears to be a definition of futures research. As described earlier, horizon scanning is one of a number of futures research techniques. Government’s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">continued use of ‘horizon scanning’ as a catch-all term for all futures research techniques is detrimental in facilitating understanding between policy</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> advisors, politicians as decision makers, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">and practitioners. This has the potential to lead to misunders</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">tandings during </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">research commissioning and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">process, which wastes time and resources on both sides</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, and can create frustration</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. Additionally, it does not demonstrate to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">researchers</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> that Government is an intelligent customer of futures research</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">compromising</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> best value</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The Day Review proposes the identification and use of high-level champions for futures research in Government. This </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">reflects established wisdom and experience, and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">we agree that high-level champion</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> for futures research would be instrumental</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> in helping to embed futures thinking across Government and in individual Departments</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. This should </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">build on the work undertaken by Prof Sir David King and the late Prof Sir Howard Dalton, who </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">both </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">pioneered the use of futures research methods to support de</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">cision-making, across Government and in Defra respectively. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">5.7</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Futures research outputs are a tool to test developing policy to ensure </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">resilience</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> to future requirements. The next step in using this research to test policy and identify future implications</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> h</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">as until recently been undertaken or led by policy experts within Departments. However, the Day Review suggests that policy-makers now have an expectation that futures research practitioners will identify and provide implications for the future. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We presume</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> that this reflects Cabinet Office guidance and thinking in outsourcing policy. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">This is challenging</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> for futures research</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">: futures researchers are only rarely domain or policy experts in the policy areas they help Departments to investigate – more often, th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ey bring new dimensions, evidence, insight and act as facilitators to help experts to identify the implications of future developments for themselves. Policy makers and politicians </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">– or their advisors or delegates - </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">need to be equipped to seek and absorb </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">his </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">expertise and insight, compute it, and then make informed decisions. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Therefore, taken at face value, the recommendation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> represents a step change that will demand a shift in the role of researchers, and has accompanying resource shift implications</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">6</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">How effective is the Government at responding to policy or regulatory challenges presented by new technologies? </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal">6.1</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We consider that futures research could help Government in the early identification of the challenges presented by new technologies and use the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> followi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ng examples to illustrate this:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Genetically Modified Organisms (GMOs): </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The application of analysis of the future implications of GMOs, could possibly have enabled the identification of the full set of implications for this new technology. Whilst i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">n hindsight, it appears that the economic and scientific analysis of this new technology was investigated in detail, the potential societal implications do not appear to have been given the same level of analysis, and following a number of well-reported me</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">dia campaigns against the use of the GM in the UK, large numbers of the population reje</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">cted the technology.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Lobbying using social media:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> The use of social media to lobby Government has risen markedly in the last 5 years. Current technology allows geograph</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ically dispersed, but like-minded individuals, to quickly and easily lobby Government in an unprecedented way. Examples of this include, the intervention of the 38 Degrees </span><a href="http://www.38degrees.org.uk/pages/save_our_forests_action_centre"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Save o</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">ur Forests</span></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> campaign in the proposed Government sell-off of forests in 2011 and more recently, the various on-line petitions concerning the badger cull. Whilst the developing technology</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and the way </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">it</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">could</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> change how the electorate </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">might </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">interact with </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Government</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> was identified as an emerging issue by various Departmental horizon scanning exercises, further research on the implications of this new technology, did not emerge. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">References: </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Defra</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> (2006). Looking Back at Looking Forwards. Accessed on 24 September 2013 at: </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">http://horizonscanning.defra.gov.uk/ViewDocument_Image.aspx?Doc_ID=192</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>